{{DISPLAYTITLE:<span style="color: white; text-shadow: 1px 3px 0 #0000FF, 1px 9px 5px #">'''Level 442: It’s Way Too Late'''</span></span></span>}}
{{Class Custom Image|class=Deadzone|hexagon=🕱|bg-image=Void.png|text-color=white|safety=Heavily Unsafe|security=Unstable|entity=Constant Gas Leaks}}
<center><pre>Level 442 is the 443th level within the Backrooms.</pre></center>
{{Background|file=Level 442.jpg}}
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="7">| General Description |</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
{{Blurimage|file=Level 442.jpg|caption=“I'm Dead”.}} '''Level 442, also known as "It’s Way Too Late," is described as a modern residential house originating from the late 1990s to the early 2000s. The level takes the appearance of a typical suburban home commonly found in ordinary neighborhoods of [[The Frontrooms]]. Despite its familiar design, the house exists in complete isolation. No streets, sidewalks, or nearby homes have ever been observed surrounding the structure, and any attempt to view the outside through windows often results in an unclear or darkened view.'''

'''The structure itself resembles an ordinary suburban house and is mostly constructed from drywall, oak wood, and reinforced concrete. The interior layout follows a fairly standard design, consisting of multiple bedrooms, bathrooms, a living room, a kitchen, hallways, and storage spaces such as closets or small utility rooms. Some areas of the house appear fully furnished with furniture typical of the late 1990s or early 2000s, including sofas, wooden tables, televisions, bookshelves, and kitchen appliances. However, the placement of certain objects may appear slightly unusual, with furniture sometimes positioned at odd angles or placed in locations where it would not normally be expected.'''

'''The level maintains a relatively stable indoor climate. The temperature typically remains between 18°C and 23°C (64°F–73°F) throughout most areas of the house. Humidity levels remain moderate, and the air often feels slightly stale, as if the building has been sealed for an extended period of time. No working ventilation systems have been confirmed, though faint air movement can occasionally be felt in certain hallways.'''

'''Lighting conditions vary depending on the room. Some areas are dimly lit by ceiling lights or lamps that appear to function without any visible power source, while other rooms remain partially dark. Light bulbs within the house rarely burn out, and attempts to remove or replace them often result in no noticeable change to the lighting conditions.'''
{{Blurimage|file=442.3.jpg|caption=“Safety Is Not Guaranteed”.}}
'''The level is also affected by [[Phenomenon 15]]. Because of this phenomenon, wanderers within the level often report an overwhelming sense of isolation and unease. Even when exploring the house for extended periods of time, wanderers almost never encounter other individuals. The silence throughout the building can become deeply unsettling, as even normal household sounds such as footsteps, creaking floors, or distant movement are rarely heard.'''

{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="7">| Environment |</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
'''Level 442's environment is extremely dangerous and is considered almost guaranteed to result in death for unprepared wanderers. The structural stability of the house is highly unreliable, and large sections of the level may collapse without warning. Floors, ceilings, and supporting walls have been observed cracking or shifting over time, creating a constant risk of sudden structural failure. These collapses may trap wanderers beneath debris for long periods of time, often leaving them unable to escape.'''

'''The interior of the house frequently shows signs of severe deterioration. Sections of drywall may crumble, wooden beams may splinter, and portions of the ceiling may partially collapse into the rooms below. Because of this instability, wanderers are advised to move cautiously when traveling through hallways or entering unfamiliar rooms.'''

'''Gas leaks are also fairly common throughout the level. These leaks often originate from damaged pipes hidden behind the walls or beneath the floors of the house. The gases released into the environment can slowly accumulate in enclosed areas, creating dangerous conditions for anyone inside the structure. Prolonged exposure may lead to suffocation, dizziness, or loss of consciousness.'''

'''In addition to their suffocating properties, some of these gases are highly flammable. If ignited, they can easily cause fires that spread rapidly throughout the house, potentially burning large sections of the level while wanderers are still inside. Because of the wooden structural components and dry materials present throughout the house, fires can quickly grow out of control.'''

'''The gases commonly detected within Level 442 include water vapor (H₂O), carbon dioxide (CO₂), methane (CH₄), and nitrous oxide (N₂O), among other unidentified compounds. While some of these gases may appear harmless in small concentrations, the mixture and accumulation of multiple gases in enclosed spaces can create extremely hazardous conditions.'''

'''Due to the unstable structure, frequent gas leaks, and the risk of fire, Level 442 is considered one of the more hazardous residential-type environments encountered within the Backrooms. Wanderers are strongly advised to remain cautious and avoid staying within the level longer than necessary.'''
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="7">| Entities & Dangers |</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
==Smilers==
{{Entity Class|Agg=5|Int=5|Dan=5|no=3|Hab=Dark areas of any level}}
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
'''[[Entity 3]], or Smilers, are fairly common in Level 442, as most areas of the level are surrounded by darkness. Because of the dim lighting and the many enclosed spaces within the house, Smilers are able to hide easily throughout the environment. They are most frequently found inside dark closets, storage rooms, or poorly lit hallways where their glowing faces can be seen emerging from the darkness.'''

'''In rare cases, Smilers have been observed wandering throughout the level without any visible difficulty. Unlike wanderers, Smilers appear to be unaffected by the unstable structure of the house. The frequent shaking of the level and the occasional collapses do not appear to disturb them. They continue moving through the environment as if the surrounding hazards are nonexistent.'''

'''Smilers also appear to be completely immune to the gas leaks present within the level. While these gases may suffocate or harm wanderers, Smilers show no signs of distress or damage when exposed to them. Because of this apparent immunity to the level’s environmental dangers, Smilers are considered an additional threat to anyone attempting to survive inside Level 442.'''

'''Wanderers are strongly advised to avoid dark areas whenever possible, as Smilers tend to remain hidden until someone approaches too closely.'''
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
==Hounds==
{{Entity Class|Agg=5|Int=3|Dan=4|no=8|Hab=Majority of levels; most notably those abandoned by unfortunate circumstances.}}
'''[[Entity 8]], or Hounds, are occasionally found in the darker sections of Level 442. They are most commonly observed roaming the hallways, the living room, and other open areas of the house. Because many parts of the level are poorly lit, Hounds are able to move through the environment without much difficulty. Wanderers have reported hearing distant growls, scratching sounds, or footsteps echoing through the hallways before encountering one.'''

'''Hounds appear to move freely throughout the level and are often seen investigating rooms or wandering through narrow corridors. In some cases, they may remain hidden in darker rooms for extended periods of time before suddenly appearing when a wanderer approaches. Their presence can make navigating the house far more dangerous, especially in areas where visibility is limited.'''

'''Similar to the Smilers present within the level, Hounds do not appear to be affected by the constant shaking of the structure or the frequent gas leaks. While these environmental hazards can trap or suffocate wanderers, Hounds continue moving through the house without showing any signs of distress. They seem completely immune to the unstable conditions of the level.'''

'''Because of the confined environment of the house and the unpredictable layout of its rooms and hallways, escaping from a pursuing Hound can be extremely difficult. Wanderers are strongly advised to remain quiet and avoid drawing attention when moving through dark areas of the level.'''
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
==Dullers==
{{Entity Class|Agg=2|Int=3|Dan=4|no=6|Hab=Majority}}
'''[[Entity 6]], or Dullers, are rare to encounter in Level 442. They are typically around 2 meters (6.5 ft) tall or more. Because the ceilings within the house are only around 1.95 meters (6.3 ft) high, Dullers often struggle to move comfortably through the level. As a result, they frequently collide with support beams and ceiling structures while walking through the hallways.'''

'''Because of their height, Dullers are usually forced to bend over while moving around the house. Despite this, they still tend to strike their heads against beams, door frames, or other parts of the ceiling. The sound of these impacts can often be heard from far away and is sometimes described as a dull thumping noise echoing through the structure.'''

'''This repeated banging can make it easier for wanderers to detect the presence of a Duller before seeing it. However, the sound can also travel through multiple rooms and hallways, making it difficult to determine the entity's exact location.'''
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="7">| Colonies & Outposts |</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
'''Due to the extremely high risk of a full structural collapse and the possibility that the entire level could burn down because of the gases present throughout the house, no colonies or outposts have ever been successfully established within Level 442. The unstable structure makes long-term settlement nearly impossible, as sections of the house may collapse without warning. In addition, the frequent gas leaks create a constant risk of suffocation or sudden fires that could quickly spread through the wooden parts of the structure. Because of these hazards, any known attempts to create a permanent settlement within the level have ultimately failed.'''
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="7">| Entrances and Exits |</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
==Entrances==
*'''Inhaling large amounts of carbon dioxide and passing out may lead here.
*'''Noclipping through a wooden support beam has a high chance of leading here.
*'''Tripping down a wooden staircase has a low chance of leading here.
==Exits==
*'''Breaking a weak wall may send one to [[Level 19]].
*'''Touching a strangely formed concrete wall may send one to [[Level 5.55]].
*'''Breaking the floor may send one to [[The Void]].
